hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a function $f: [a, b] \to \mathbb{R}$ defined as a generalization of the Dirichlet function. Let $\alpha$ and $\beta$ be two distinct real numbers with $\alpha > \beta$. The function is defined as:
$$
f(x) = \begin{cases} 
\alpha  \text{if } x \in \mathbb{Q} \text{ (x is rational)} \\
\beta  \text{if } x \notin \mathbb{Q} \text{ (x is irrational)} 
\end{cases}
$$
The upper Riemann integral of a bounded function $f$ on $[a,b]$, denoted $\overline{\int_a^b} f(x) \,dx$, is defined as the infimum of all upper Darboux sums over all possible partitions of $[a,b]$. Similarly, the lower Riemann integral, $\underline{\int_a^b} f(x) \,dx$, is the supremum of all lower Darboux sums. A function is Riemann integrable if and only if its upper and lower Riemann integrals are equal.

Calculate the value of the upper Riemann integral minus the lower Riemann integral for the function $f(x)$ over the interval $[a, b]$. Express your answer as a formula in terms of $a, b, \alpha,$ and $\beta$.
